title: Q&A: What you're probably asking about the Tan trial
text:
These are some of the most common questions, culled from social media, from the trial of Charles Tan. We've tried to answer them as best we can with the information now available. 1. Where are Jean Tan and Charles's brother, Jeffrey? Why didn't they testify, and why haven't they been seen in or out of the courtroom?
Both Jean and Jeffrey Tan were on the witness list, which could have prevented them from going into the courtroom. However, they could still have been in the court building for support. That said, the defense may not have wanted the mother there — and especially may not have wanted her to testify — since they pointed to her as the likely killer.
Regarding their whereabouts, two witnesses testified that Jean and Jeffrey Tan have been on site running the Canandaigua-based Dynamax Imaging company Jim Tan founded in 2013. Gargan said he did not call them to the stand because he had not been allowed to interview them (they had legal representation) and presumed their testimony would likely attempt to paint Charles Tan in a favorable light.
ROCHESTER DEMOCRAT AND CHRONICLE
How will lawyers approach Charles Tan case next time?
2. If they believe Jim Tan was dead for days before Jean Tan's 911 call, why wasn't she charged for obstruction of justice?
This is a question we plan to pose to the prosecution. There is nothing that now prevents her from being charged with obstruction.
3. Why haven't we heard anything from Jim Tan's family, or friends defending him?
The Democrat and Chronicle has reached out to his co-workers, and has looked for extended family — all to no avail. We intend to keep trying, especially with a retrial possible. There was testimony from several co-workers at trial, and some said Jim Tan had a propensity for anger and sometimes belittled workers in front of others. No one throughout the trial identified themselves as a supporter of Jim Tan.

You may also like these photo galleries: Replay Autoplay Show Thumbnails Show Captions Last Slide Next Slide 4. Why didn't police interrogate Charles Tan or his mother?
They both had legal representation, and the attorneys would not allow them to be questioned.
5. Why didn't the friend who bought the gun testify? Why hasn't he been charged? Does he have some sort of deal in place with prosecutors?
Whitney Knickerbocker still can be charged with illegally buying the shotgun for his friend Charles Tan. He has an attorney and may simply have invoked the Fifth Amendment at trial. There perhaps was a decision by prosecutors that his testimony would have muddied the waters instead of providing a clear picture. Several jurors said they assumed he did buy the shotgun for Tan, but that still did not give the clear proof that Tan was the killer. Thus, Knickerbocker’s testimony may not have added much. And there has been no evidence that, at least for this trial, he struck a deal with prosecutors.
ROCHESTER DEMOCRAT AND CHRONICLE
Andreatta: Why no straw-buyer charges in Tan case?
​ 6. Did Charles Tan try to flee the country the day after the murder?
At Tan's bail hearing, Assistant District Attorney William Gargan said he had evidence that Tan went to Canada on Feb. 6 and came back before the Feb. 9 call from his mother to 911. The specifics of the evidence were not revealed, nor was the issue raised at trial.
7. Was there evidence of Jean Tan being a victim of domestic violence or just speculation? Did the police fail to take action despite being called to the house repeatedly?
The only evidence of domestic violence entered at trial was Jean Tan’s 911 call on Jan. 28 in which she said her husband had thrown her to the floor and choked her. Deputies who visited the home said they saw some redness on her neck, but it did not look like a serious injury and that Jean Tan asked them not to arrest her husband. She also, as evidence showed, sought an order of protection and considered a divorce.
This case does raise questions about the response of law enforcement to this household, and domestic violence cases in general. The county has refused to release records that would lend insight into multiple calls over the past decade to the Tan household in Pittsford. The Democrat and Chronicle plans to again seek those records, which should illuminate the reasons law enforcement went to the house.

8. Was there evidence that Charles and his mom hid or destroyed evidence in the days between the murder and the arrests? Why didn’t we hear about any text messages/calls/emails between Charles and his mom before or after the murder?
There was no evidence introduced at trial of this sort. We don’t know what the prosecution or defense had evidence-wise but chose not to introduce.
The only two calls between Charles and Jean Tan entered into evidence were the two on Feb. 5, one at 9:50 p.m. and one at 11:16 p.m. The duration of both calls was a couple of minutes.
9. Can the jury consider that Charles Tan acted in self-defense if that is not a theory presented by the defense attorney?
The jury could consider other alternatives, even if it believed him to be the killer but not guilty of murder with intent. They should not consider anything beyond what they think the evidence points to.

What was the evidence on the gun itself? Whose fingerprints were on it?
It’s unclear if any fingerprints were found on the gun.
11. Could Tan be found guilty of murder even if he didn't pull the trigger?
He could have been found guilty as an accomplice to murder, if County Court Judge James Piampiano had allowed that choice for the jury. However, he refused to do so, saying the prosecution did not lay a foundation for that consideration. Being a knowing accomplice is, under the law, the same as being the killer. The prosecution could bolster its case with a retrial with more emphasis on possible collusion, and could seek a new indictment accusing Charles Tan of being either the killer or an accomplice.
Two jurors who voted to acquit Tan said afterward that they believed him an accomplice.
12. Did Tan's female friend from RIT lie on the stand, about Charles's demeanor on the day the murder may have occurred?
Anna Valentine’s testimony that Charles Tan’s demeanor on Feb. 5 was not unusual did run counter to what she told different media outlets, including the Democrat and Chronicle, after Tan’s arrest.

13. Did Jean Tan inherit her husband's company as a result of his murder? Could that be in jeopardy if she faces charges?
At least two witnesses testified that Jeffrey and Jean Tan now run the business, but not specifically that it is theirs. If it is still owned by the family, it could still be run by Jeffrey Tan.
14. Who is the redheaded girl that's with Charlie every day?
We have been told she is a Cornell student, from Connecticut.

15. Is Dateline here covering the trial for their show?
They did come seeking permission to film in the courtroom but were denied. It’s unknown whether the show will still do a segment on the case.
16. If there’s a re-trial, could Charles Tan adopt a different defense (like self-defense) or is he stuck with the theory that his mom did it?
Gargan and defense lawyer Brian DeCarolis both said they are not restrained by the first trial. New witnesses could be called, new theories presented. The charge cannot change, however, unless Charles is reindicted on new charges.
